I’ve been smoking weed on & off since I was 13. I stopped at dif times in my life for probation, while in prison & then decided to go completely sober for several years once released before returning only to certain psychedelics for the past 6 or so. 

I’m not normal and don’t do anything normally, I do what I want and go as hard as humanly possible. No balance. I wake up & smoke immediately and it’s the last thing I do before falling asleep. I’ll put down 5 grams a day myself on a light day. I’m never not high, but I also don’t get high anymore, I maintain a baseline I’ve established. 

Weed has not only been something I’ve loved for a long time but it’s defined me personally & professionally over the past several years also. I grew up hiding it and getting arrested almost monthly. Now it’s legal, normal & flows like water.

After staying as high as possible while building & running businesses from scratch it’s finally been catching up to me. While I remain an advocate for cannabis and legalization I am for the first time feeling the negative effects from my constant use & choosing to stop. My tolerance is ridiculously high, my short term memory has been effected and in my busy life I am forced to do things immediately or risk them being lost in the abyss forever. I operate in a flow state at all times which is both good & bad and like living in an ongoing blurry dream. Most importantly though, I’ve become easy to anger as the stress and responsibilities have built over time and my constant smoking has seemed to change my body and mind’s response to them leading to some of my reactions not matching my desires.

I set lofty goals for myself and get after them with no outs (burn the ships), only the goal in mind, faith and determination but I realize now I wasn’t caring for myself & should’ve been. No breaks, no vacations, no rewarding myself ever - just working my hardest like a soldier while high.

Life is about growth and the time has come to turn a page and level up. Not sure about long term but for right now I’m done and completely sober again.

Onto the next chapter of this crazy ride and it’s going to be a great one. 

CBD from now on 💪
@gameupnutrition

Found these today. This was in 2011 or so several years into my sentence with my bros @iansmithfitness and Jeremy. Shortly after this I was put in solitary for a month for fighting where I wrote a 70k word, very detailed memoir with absolutely nothing else to do. I was in the hole 3x during my sentence and they were all torture. Picture living in a cement closet with nothing and nothing to do for 30 days.. The book has sat around now for more than a decade and I’ve typed out the handwritten pages over time but after reading through it again recently it brought me right back and I need to do something with it. I had zero distractions when writing it and started with the idea to glorify my insane life to that point but when I finished I read it back in horror and it finally truly set in how big of a fuck up I’d been to that point, ultimately becoming the reason for my drastic change in direction and thinking. It also covers in great detail my time inside such as watching a kid get beat to death during my first week in prison. It’s the insane and true story of my life up to that point. I’ll be looking to drop it in the next few months after some pro editing is done and this post will force me to follow through. If interested you can pre-order the paperback now using the link in my bio and I’ll do something special for anyone who does. Also, my bro Ian also just dropped a book about his time in and his recent ride to notoriety by defying lockdowns with his gym and running for congress. Check his page for more info and thank you 👊

5 days no cigs, no cheating, no patches or gum etc. Just making up my mind to stop and not being a bitch. Was worried I’d put on weight after quitting so I kicked up my work outs and eaten cleaner and am right where I was before. Don’t let the proposed enormity of something stop you from doing it and be careful who you even listen to, just because something was hard (or even too hard) for someone else doesn’t mean it will be for you. You’re in control of yourself. Be a mfin beast and just do it. Coming up on 1 month completely sober also 👊👊👊

Wrapping another fun, crazy and fulfilling year. My main goal is to spend my time doing cool shit with cool people and I’m happy to have achieved that once again. Life should be fun and interesting and I work hard at making that the case for myself. And life is crazy: over the last year I sold half my equity in High Rollerz and passed off all responsibility in running things, started a new job that I loved that lasted a month because the owner committed suicide, became an uncle again, finished a book ten years in the making and am now finishing things off by appearing in a Jean-Claude Van Damme movie, quitting smoking everything and dedicating myself back to my health - mental and physical. 

Shoutout to the real ones in my life, I appreciate you more than you know because most are fake. I’m the furthest thing from it and I say that proudly. Onto the next one - happy new year everyone 👊

And once again RIP @stephanbonnar

I have two speeds: I either rapidly self destruct or I viciously win. I am and have always been my own worst enemy and/or my strongest ally. I’m currently in an epic win mode. I’ve given a ton of my time and energy to others that don’t even seem to understand or appreciate it in the end. Some of that is because as the audio says I’ve been successful mostly because I do only what I want to do. I’m not the type to do something I don’t want to well, or at all. So when I find something that lights me up inside I go all the fuck in. Few do that in my experience and so they don’t understand it, or me. The downside is once I commit I am a bit trapped and my intense persistence and dedication is often taken for granted and used against me. Right now I’m free, focusing only on me and becoming the best version of myself possible. We all have only one life, my suggestions is to go live the one of your dreams - or at least try. Don’t let others hold you back, change your path or dampen your light, ever. If that happens, bounce fast.

For a good at home workout, or anywhere for that matter, do burpees. Try 25 and then work towards a 100. I did these everyday when locked up. Great for both strength and endurance and you only need the will to do them - no equipment or gym etc. 

#burpees #motivation

No smoking update from DTLA. 12th day no smoking and no cheating. Strength and energy have both risen a ton. Cravings are basically gone. One thing I didn’t expect is intense bloating. I am learning now that nicotine speeds food passage through your gut. Uncomfortable but it will pass. More weird than anything. Didn’t realize how much smoking effects my body because I always did it. For those out there that want to quit, there’s never a good time, just do it.

Some flashback photos of sporadically training over the years with legends. Most assume I’m good at Jiu Jitsu because of High Rollerz and knowing some of the world’s best black belts for years but sadly no, I never stuck with it like a lazy dumbass. Trained consistently for a few months then stopped, jumped in a handful of seminars here and there with huge breaks in between, hopped in to random no-Gi classes because I was there then stopped. I wish I was in the mindset I’m in now back then. I’d have almost 7 years or so of training with some of the best in the world. Fuck! But it’s never too late and it’s time to make this a steady part of my life. Posting this stuff is always about making me accountable and keeping me to my word and intentions.

I did complain a few years ago to @nickdiaz209 one time about exactly this, that I roll with martial arts legends but never really learn anything and he scoffed and told me the me of that moment would kick the shit out of the me from before I knew them and that’s true. They’ve definitely taught me a lot by osmosis over the years. I’m blessed to have the life and friends I have but I fuckin wish I had really taken advantage of it more over the years. 🤷‍♂️

Im not a big TV guy so I don’t pay attention but I’m super pumped to find out today very late that the story Shantaram has been turned into a show finally. Shantaram is a mostly true story written into a thousand page book that I’ve read three times and has always been my favorite book. First Johnny Depp was making it years ago and then Russell Crowe but both never happened. I am so pumped to see this finally happen. It’s told beautifully and was famously written ten times during the authors prison term and kept getting destroyed by guards and he had to restart it. It is the story of Lyn, a heroin addict bank robber in Australia who escapes prison, gets a fake passport and flies to India and chooses to live there for the next decade+ learning the languages, living in the slums, helping the people, getting to know the underbelly of Mumbai and working his way up the Indian mob. I read the book when I myself was living in India almost 20 years ago and then again twice more when I was locked up so it holds a special place in my heart because of that and brings me right back to being in Mumbai and was a powerful escape from being locked up myself. So dope to see Charlie Hunnam playing the part also. This story is badass and beautiful and insane and very entertaining. I hope they nailed the show and can’t wait to find out. I would advise anyone who loves reading to read the book though, no show will touch how well Gregory David Roberts wrote this story, it’s like one very long poem and just an incredible book. @gdr_shantaram

Had another comp today. Lost on points 🤬 Here’s the match for anyone interested in white belt Jiu Jitsu lol. My game has been developing from the bottom, I’m not on top often, my plan was to pull guard then sub from there or move to Williams guard and sub from there. Went for some triangles and arm bars but this guy and the competition in general had me gassed quickly and I wasn’t able to lock them in. It’s so crazy how different my mind and cardio is in competition than during training. Spent time really warming up this time but the intensity surprised me again. Much of competing I realize is controlling the brain and the body. Gave it everything I had and left nothing in the tank. Even with my cardio the best it’s ever been I realize I still need to work on it. I would have won this if I had just a bit more energy at the end. Pissed off I didn’t get a finish, not gonna lie. Thank you to @gunsnrollz and @richhatesjiujitsu for coming out to coach me 👊
